text: It will be better than the last one - which will make it a "cinematic triumph" and "10/10" in the eyes millions who have never seen Lawrence of Arabia - but a lot of fan fiction would make a better movie than The Last Jedi, so it's really no great feat. The point, however, is that making a decent, even consistent, Star Wars movie never HAD to be any great feat, even though Abrams will get credit for "saving" a franchise that was essentially bulletproof and never SHOULD have needed saving in the first place. After acquiring Star Wars, Disney just played into the stability of the brand's overwhelming marketability and anything and everything got thrown at the screen by people who neither understood, nor really cared about, Star Wars. With all of the "talent" in Hollywood today, how sloppy do you have to be to screw up something like Star Wars, given that The Force Awakens was really just a rehash of A New Hope anyway, and was allowed to slide by on THAT basis?

text: *potential spoiler warning*         Palpatine created force sensitive clones to inhabit their bodies and live forever, a trick stolen from his previous master Darth Plagueis who purportedly solved the mystery of immortality. Cloning is not hard when you have Kamino and the best minds in the galaxy for cloning.  Rey was a clone in transit who was thought lost when the ship was destroyed when the empire fell. Being a death world, she could not be sensed by Snoke (Also Palpatine in a failing and cobbled together body), Kylo or Luke (Also why Kenobi picked Tatooine to hide Luke, his aunt and uncle being there a happy coincidence) and being engineered as the host of Palpatine would be engineered to be more powerful than his previous form, innately becoming stronger as a result (which is also why Rey can magically do shit she‚Äôs not trained to do and proficiently.) The ghost of Palpatine possessing people, particularly the sons of Solo, is canon in the EU as is the creation of Force Sensitive clones in FU:2. These are pretty old and accepted concepts within the universe of SW.  She has no linage or family. Only endless versions of herself as seen in the cave sequence. Endlessly dead clones. Only her. The literal exact same scene occurs when Galen Marek enters the cave on Dagobah and sees endless versions of himself before finding out that he‚Äôs a clone. Luke, while training Rey, senses only an all too familiar darkness inside her....you thought he was talking about Vader, he was talking about Palpatine.   Rey is the bad guy. She is going to be possessed by Palpatine and Palpatine is going to try and kill Kylo, being of no more use to him as he intended on possessing him after the loss of his creation.  It‚Äôs time for the rise of the last Skywalker.

text: The sequel trilogy seems to be echoing the fabled Goldilocks tale. Some say "The Force Awakens" is too soft as it to them is nothing more than a retread of A New Hope with its similar plot elements.   Then we have "The Last Jedi" which some believe is too hard as it tried to alter traditional Star Wars mythology and to them made no sense whatsoever.   Could then"The Rise of Skywalker" be just right? Time will tell.   Do I hate the sequel trilogy? No, but I can understand why some people do. It is Star Wars after all and they just simply will not please every single fan of the series. My personal favourite Star Wars material is the Old Republic stuff, from the Knights of the Old Republic games, because they are far more complicated and have more freedom to delve into the mythology than the movies do/can.

text: I honestly came here to see everyone complain. I have loved Star Wars since I was 3 and I am actually looking forward to this. You all need to stop being elitist assholes who think you know everything about how a movie/story should be made. People wanted something different for the new trilogy and yet, when The Last Jedi came out (obviously not a great Star Wars movie but still entertaining) you got so caught up in your stupid theories you couldn't accept an original concept based on a beloved series that gave us Jar Jar fucking Binks! This is a movie! It shouldn't be the site for "it should be this" "it should be that" or "I don't like that design". You're entitled to your opinion but until you design something for a project as complex as filmmaking, I'm not listening to a damn thing you say. Do what a movie is designed to make you do/feel: be distracted from your boring and mundane lives and be entertained by taking it at face value even if you think you know everything about it and the world/universe it is set in. Movies are an escape from our reality. So fucking escape it for a couple of hours and shut the hell up!

text: Here's a tip. Go back to making props, environments, animatronics, etc to make the scene look real. When you CG *everything,* there's no sense of reality or being there. There's no real comprehension of what you're watching. You don't feel like it's a place or a creature, or an alien, or a place. CG is way over used. Movies like Star Wars, Jurassic Park, and other classics benefit from using CG only when absolutely necessary. Take the time to make a movie, not a visual wonder, and you might start to care more about the character development too. It's like these companies write a script for cinematic scenes and then place characters where they need to be and THEN write story and dialogue - when it should be the complete opposite.

But since Star Wars has become even more of a phenomenon, I‚Äôve always felt like I missed the boat as a kid. Everyone I know who loves it grew up with it and as such, it taps into their nostalgia. In short, I don't think people were asking for too much going into this trilogy, even if the movies were bad, if it had Han/Leia/Luke all venturing together again people would have liked it. Now it's not even possible to see that happen. text: So as the only guy who may be defending this movie, I have to say that the twist of Ray being the villain would not only make a FANTASTIC twist, but would not only tie into the Title, but would also be the culmination of a wider story.   First, the tie in with the title, Ben (AKA Kylo) would have to face a enemy who was not only his equal but who has shown to be better then him on multiple occasions. Therefore, should they fight early in the film, and Ray win, then go onto take Kylo‚Äôs place in the First order, Kylo would have to RISE from the darkness as a Skywalker and face Ray again.  Second, if you look at the course of the last 2 movies, Ray and Kylo have been trying to be one thing, Ray the Jedi, Kylo the sith. They both have said they feel out of place and need to know what role they are supposed to play in this story, so for Ray to finally embrace who she was MEANT to be, a Sith, would force Kylo to accept his role as the Jedi.  And as part of a wider story, if you look at the prequels and the OT, they both follow Arcs of characters searching for there path, and we have seen a trilogy of a hero turned villain, and a Ordinary boy turned hero, so why not have a trilogy of a Hero turn true villain?  Just a rant to voice my thoughts, and to say STOP BASHING THIS TRILOGY FOR NOT BEING LIKE THE ORIGINAL!!! IT IS ITS OWN STORY!!!! ENJOY IT FOR WHAT IT IS!!!!

text: Someone has to say it, all of the new Star Wars movies are horrible!!!! The Original Star Wars movies were an adventure, they drew you into the plot and story-line; they you to make some emotional connections and generated momentum as the story progressed; you identified with the characters and liked the Gritty, if not dirty background and characters, which looked not necessarily real, but touchable because they used puppets vs. computer animated junk. Even with todays computer animation, the characters look fake, its like watching some teen actress fight a Disney character. Also, is it believable the a 110lb flat chested white girl without any particular training or experience is now able to out fight supposedly professionally trained JEDI with years of training and battle experience. And, what is with the black guy character? I'm fine with black man having a leading support role for the movie, but it seems forced. His Character is shallow, uninteresting, has little or no impact in the film = Token black guy clearly parroting the original role of Han Solo. I'm just saying Star Wars needs to stop catering to the millennial, because the TRUE Fan Base are now in their 40's and want more realistic, gritty characters and story-lines vs. just a bunch of computer animated garbage.

text: Based on that shot of Rey and Ben fighting it doesn't look like the lightsaber combat has gotten any better but oh well.  I will say this, and this has been a consistent thing throughout the whole sequel trilogy, I love how much the lightsabers interact with the environment in the new movies.  How the light illuminates everything around it including the actors' faces, subtle things like sparks flying and interacting with the environment, how when Ben ignites his lightsaber the frozen air starts steaming up around it while also reacting to the light intensifying the red glow in the shot. That's really just a matter of better technology of course. I just can't help but imagine if we had lightsaber duels with the more clear narrative focus of the originals, the sophisticated choreography of the prequel trilogy, and the cinematography and technology of the sequel trilogy. It'd be fuckin glorious, man.

Palpatine is Snokes true Master? His puppet? In true Sith Lord Fashion, he makes Rey and Kilo Ren fight  to the death in order to make one his new Apprentice.. 1:37 Not like her uncle Luke Skywalker that resisted Palpatines temptation in Return of the Jedi to kill his father... Rescues Rey from Darth Sidius? Kills Darth Sidious? Reforms a New Order similar to the Jedi? Rebellion beat the Emperors Fleet.   I've read somewhere in the lorespere that it was Luke (Not Rey) who became the one corrupted by a clone of Palpatine (The original was killed by Vader in Return of the Jedi). text: I think they are making it subtly clear in The Rise of Skywalker. Lucas always said it‚Äôs the story of Anakin/Vader, and KK says it‚Äôs all about family. Obviously Star Wars makes huge $$$, so it‚Äôs the reason it continues after Lucas, but I think it‚Äôs the full story of the redemption and balance of the story of Anakin/Vader. Even in the sequels. The lightsaber calls to Rey, the mighty Skywalker blood in Kylo, the force connection of Rey/Kylo, (even the name Kylo - sKYwalker/soLO) brings it all together. I think the RISE of skywalker, is simply the balance of light (Rey) and dark (Kylo) coming together in a way, to defeat the manipulator of the force (midi-chlorians) in the character who is trying to wield the power of the force, ‚Äòunnaturally‚Äô thus bringing imbalance - none other than  Palpatine. The reason for Palpatines return gives play to him understanding the secret to keep one from dying, even in spirit form. The unnatural bend in the force must end...making way for a new chapter of Star Wars with the young force sensitive individuals. - The manifestation of Anakin, in Rey/Kylo, and it‚Äôs dual-sided power, the Rise of Skywalker, will be to complete the prophecy of Anakin, the one who will bring balance to the force...ending the Skywalker saga... I really hope I'm wrong in saying this, but I have very little doubt Rey will ever experience a single loss or moment that might even hint at failure, as we've seen in the past 2 movies Disney produced.    I don't know if I'm alone in this, but the only character I really feel attached to is Kylo. He's the only character who we really understand the backstory and motives to his actions. Rey? Not one bit. Snoke? nope. Finn? A little, but he's a male, so Kathleen will just make sure he's a bumbling idiot who did one good thing and anything he tries to do that might be good will be portrayed as foolish by a female lead (IE last jedi battering ram 'scene').    Rey's character hasn't been developed one bit. The only thing that's developed are her powers. For some reason, Disney thinks these two types of story development are the same. I feel like they accidentally develop kylo's character every time he fights Rey because Disney makes him lose. text: This is my ideal new star wars trilogy should have been...  Episode VIII: The Shadow Empire - Opening scene Princess Leia Organa has passed away with Luke, Ben Solo and Lando attending the funeral. Luke discovered some evidence of a foul play in her sister's death with only one witness who can give the answer; a girl named Rey who fled the scene before Leia's death. and so Luke decides to find Rey to discover the truth with Ben Solo his Nephew and apprentice. Meanwhile a series of unknown attacks has been terrorizing the New Republic, there are also reports of sightings of fleet of warships of unknown origin just outside the borders of known space, The death of Princess Organa has also brought problems of its own, it seems that the New republic has only remained united to her sheer will alone. without her cracks begun to show and the divisions within the senate is threatening to fracture the galaxy into civil war. Han Solo together with Chewie has just returned from a four year journey from the unknown space bearing with them troubling news. There was also a Jedi expedition to the unknown space 19 years ago but the ship never returned and was considered a failure this is also where luke lost his wife who was the leader of the said expedition the last transmission they gave was to Leia Organa which she claimed to have deleted and remained silent of what the message was. Is there someone manipulating the events from behind the scene? Will Luke and Ben know the truth behind Leia's death? and what did Han and Chewie discovered in the unknown space?    Episode IX: Legacy of Skywalker - Opening Scene The unknown fleet of ships has revealed their true identity as the Empire of the Hand founded by the late Emperor Palpatine in the unknown space. Admiral Thrawn the supreme leader of this mysterious empire has issued an ultimatum to the New Republic to surrender unconditionally. The Republic who just recently suffered massive losses after their fleet were caught off guard and devastated by the sudden attack of Thrawn's Grand fleet. most of the military shipyards of the republic were either destroyed or inoperative in simultaneous bombings by the empire of the hand's agents within the Republic. Luke, Ben and Rey together with their new companion Finn a clone trooper from the now defunct Galactic Empire who finally realized the war is over traveled together to an ancient massive shipyard called "Star Forge" there they found out who was behind the death of Leia a clone of the Emperor Palpatine. Leia discovered the star forge through the help of the wife of Luke who sent her the last transmission of the Jedi expedition before it went missing and never returned. Leia was planning to reveal it to the senate the very year she died with the plan of destroying the ancient structure to make sure it won't fall in the wrong hands. a battle ensue between Luke and his companions against the Clone of Emperor Palpatine and his droids. The droids were no match against the Jedi master but before Luke and Ben get closed to the Emperor Rey pulled a red lightsaber revealing her as a Sith. She then revealed that she was trained by the Late Emperor in the ways of the Sith and showed her the kindness that no one has bothered to give her when her mother died. Finn and Ben surprise at the revelation have no choice but to face their friend both with conflicting feelings for Rey. The Clone Emperor younger and stronger dueled with Luke who's age has finally starting to slow the legendary Jedi, but Luke still manage to best the Sith Lord giving him a fatal blow with his last breath telling the Jedi that it is a mistake to destroy the star forge and that it is their only chance to defeat what is coming. Withe the death of the clone emperor Rey suffered a telepathic blast from the emperor force ghost telling her repeatedly to avenged him and kill Luke and so force push Ben and Finn and went straight to duel Luke. The Jedi master not understanding the pain and anger of Rey to him ask the girl why and here another revelation... "I am Rey Jade and you killed my mother!" she then slash Luke while he was shocked to know Mara Jade his first student and wife who he thought to have been lost in the Jedi expedition to unknown space was survived by their Daughter and in someway was discovered by the emperor and turned against him. Luke then embrace his Daughter and told her that there's never a day goes by that he regret not telling her mother to stay and to hell with the expedition and that if there ever was a way to help her it is to save their daughter and pull her out of the dark side and into light. Rey is now even more confused flashback of her past their ship fired upon by a fleet of pirate ships, how they escape and crash landed on a desolate world her mother dying soon after and her rescue by the Late emperor Palpatine. Ben and Finn finally caught up with two but Luke is already dying from his wound inflicted by Rey, she then run from them and activated the self destruct sequence for the star forge. Ben and Finn took the dying Jedi master with them and rush to the hanger only time to see the Millennium Falcon waiting for them. The star forge explode merely a second after the Millennium Falcon escape. Rey also survive flying an imperial tie fighter.    Episode XI: Thrawn's Gambit - opening scene The republic is in dire danger of total collapse. the senate is split between surrendering to Thrawn and his shadow empire or fight to the bitter end. General Lando and admiral ackbar have already assembled the remaining fleet of the new republic; an assortment of old refurbished capital ships, confiscated imperial destroyers and small re-purpose vessel. they may be old but numerous enough to give the empire of the hand a descent fight. Thrawn was saddened when he heard the death of the late Emperor and his Clone a news brought by Rey who now called herself mary sue of the dark side lol lets just say Darth Rey oohh spooky! so back to the story. Thrawn is the closest to father Rey can ever have in her younger days. The emperor was strick and merciless when it comes to training Rey in the ways of the Sith. He even went to far by brainwashing Rey into believing his father luke exiled her mother and abandoned her to her fate it drove her almost to the edge. but it was Thrawn who taught her to survive and the only one genuine enough to truly care for her though she never seen the true intention of the emperor thinking it was tough love and never had any suspicion of the old goat but to simply ready her to be her successor. this is the part I'm starting to get lazy so I'll leave you guys to think how it ends needs to sleep haha :P

text: Rey is the worst character they could've possibly created. Straight off the bat she's incredibly strong. 10 seconds of training from luke she's more powerful than any jedi with the force. She beat Kylo Ren like he was some noob with a plastic sword. No suspence, no nail biting sequences. Just boring. It's as if you already know Rey will win and that makes me so apathetic towards watching any of these new films. It's all a cash grab, no real storytelling with twists and turns leaving you at the edge of your seat. They have kylo Ren be the main 'villain' in all 3 movies for fucks sake. Up the stakes, bring in a real sith to fuck some shit up. Let Rey get fucked up or something just change it up already. I want Anikan back, with awesome lightsaber duels, new plot and suspence. Get rid of this Mary Sue. She's only there to please the feminists and SJW's and I'm so sick of it. I don't care what anyone says, episode III will always be the best in my opinion. Great storytelling, the first dark star wars film with real violence and dark scenes as he became Vader, we watch Anakin go through hell and battle his demons and succumbing to the dark side for a debatable reason. He wanted to save Padme because he's already lost so much including his mother, so he didn't want to see it happen again. His arc was awesome, and he eventually became the most feared sith in the series, even Kylo Ren knew he couldn't live up to Vader. Rey has to go. When she dies I'll feel nothing. George Lucas didn't create her, she's just a pandering Disney creation which sucks.

text: (Begin Rant) Wow it‚Äôs true. Star Wars fans are completely toxic. The comments are full of hate for a film they have already decided to despise. How do you know a "Star Wars Fan"? Well they hate the prequel trilogy, hate the new Star Wars films, and they cant stand the original trilogy now that it‚Äôs been special editioned. They also hate the new books, want the EU back as cannon, and they feel the comics are fanfic along with the animated stuff. So basically they are fans of 3 films that only exist in their imaginations, and in actuality do not resemble what they recall at all. I have never seen a fan community more determined to burry what they "Love‚Äô. Thank God some fans still remain true. It‚Äôs truly Jedi vs Sith. Oh and while I have plenty of issues with The Last Jedi, 90% of what you all complain about is totally in Universe. If you pay attention the film did not break anything. Thou I admit that whole subversion of expectations thing is some of Round Heads BS. Last Jedi needed more Luke Skywalker. Put the deleted scenes back into the flick, add a younger Luke flashback, fix the choreography in the throne room fight, rethink that Casino Sequence, and add in a scene that better explains Haldo‚Äôs motivations. Sadly George Lucas would have totally fixed those shortcomings for streaming release, but we all criticized changes being made to the movies to such a degree that Disney won‚Äôt touch them after release. If it were not for celebration being what it is, I would swear Star Wars fans have all been consumed by hate. Imagine Marvel Fans turning on the MCU because of those first couple  of Thor movies. Yes they were bad. More recent example? Captain Marvel. That flick makes no sense. End Game has some big logic problems, and they have so many fake deaths that we just assume anyone that dies will be back. Hell they introduced time travel and a multiverse. But Luke Skywalker was not like I remember him 30 years ago! How dare he change based on his life experiences! How unrealistic. text: I'm not going to watch this movie until it comes to Netflix.   I never watched The Last Jedi until long it got out of the theatres.   I love Star Wars, if my channel name doesn't give it away. It was, and still is, what I grew up on and what has influenced me the most. The OT, the Prequels, the shows, I love it all. When Disney bought Star Wars, I was excited. More than excited, I was thrilled that the story I had grown up on would continue on. The hype surrounding The Force Awakens, all their projects really, kept me excited for the movies and other media.   When The Force Awakens came out, I left the theatre... apathetic. It was not bad, but nor was it good. The movie was just... average. I didn't hate Rey, I found her as one-note as Anakin and Luke, but I didn't hate her. Was she overpowered? Yes, but it hadn't really begun to irk me yet. I worried, for a time, that maybe my love for Star Wars the movies and shows had died out. I still played the games and loved every minute of them, so perhaps there inlied the issue?    Alas, it was not. I still loved the first six and the two Clone Wars shows. It was then that I realized that The Force Awakens was not bad, it was boring. The movie was the diet version of A New Hope in every way. Every character was a cheap, dumbed-down version of their predecessor. Hux to Tarkin, Kylo to Vader, Rey to Luke, etc.    What's more, Rebels proved to be uninteresting and childish. It is a kid's show, granted, but Clone Wars was as well and it managed darker themes and still remained child-friendly. The first Battlefront had also failed spectacularly, but we all knew that.   Rogue One and Solo were improvements, but they were removed from the main trilogy, and better yet, different. Cliched, yes, but they were something Star Wars had never done before. A gritty war film and a heist comedy!    Then came The Last Jedi.    My issues with The Last Jedi are long and expansive. Everything off about The Force Awakens was increased by ten-fold here. It felt like a fanfiction, given how poorly it was written with its new OCs crammed in. Rey became too powerful, who is there left to even challenge her? Palpatine risen from the dead, the puppeted corpse of Vader? Every instant reeked of rushed production, mixed ideas about how the movie should progress, and any number of other issues that I won't get into because this comment has gotten long enough.   Watching this, I didn't feel excitement. I felt... bored. Tired, rundown even. Watching all the moments from the old movies, I came to realize that Disney has given up. Best milk nostalgia instead of creating something new and exciting, after all, it failed the other two times.    If Disney doesn't care, why should I? Why should I give a damn about these new movies when Disney can't be bothered to try?   I'm not going to watch this movie until it comes to Netflix, whether it is to have my fears confirmed or not remains to be seen.

I grew up watching the prequels first but the original trilogy , even with its lack of high tech visuals like the prequels , still holds this unique magic. text: Honestly it's incredibly annoying how many people are frustrated with this trailer and trilogy. Literally everything that has happened is pretty much on point with what George Lucas always envisioned as what happened. It has always been about the prophecy and the prophecy child, even he said he had something greater in mind when he was originally writing Darth Vader and then he wrote the prequel trilogoy that answered what that was. All this final trilogy is doing is truly finishing the Anakin storyline that has existed (albeit mainly only ever eluded to and hinted at through select lines in the movies) always, and bring an end to the prophecy. What is happening is the ending of that prophecy, it wasn't fulfilled when Anakin became Vader and it wasn't fulfilled when Luke brought him back to being Anakin. Neither of those things actually brought balance to the force they simply shifted it from 'good' to 'bad' and back to 'good'. What the force is trying to do is sort of make a restart and get people to instead of following their own whims and using the force for themselves. But to follow the force and what it guides them to do and not in terms of living species definitions of 'good' and 'bad. That is what everything has been about. That is why the force brought an end to the Jedi Order in 'Revenge of the Sith'. Because as people have critiqued, the Jedi weren't really following the Jedi code and before The Clone Wars ever started they became to involved with politics and began using the force for their own whims instead of paying attention to what it wanted. That is why through Qui-Gon Jin, someone who actually followed the direction of the force (which led him to be named a Grey Jedi and is why he had trouble with and was never put on the Jedi Council) and Anakin, it acted. It's a God ( in a sense, it's not really a God its more like Dao mashed with some other things) without a physical form, so this is how it interacts. Through the mitochlorians. So this whole trilogy is being used, and really especially this last movie, to bring an end to the Skywalker saga and the prophecy about Anakin. So in some form he will act in this movie to cause the balance to be brought to the force. Hence, The Last Jedi title, which is referencing that Rey will be the last force-sensitive to be trained in the ways of the Jedi, because inherently it is flawed- in a much more subtle manner than the Sith. And while there are two sides to the force (Light and Dark, that is undeniable, it is canon and they actually have manifestations) the light is inherently more powerful and this is its grand scheme (literally tricking and manipulating the Dark side, through Darth Sidious, whom it is canon used the force to impregnate Anakin's mother) to regain control and balance so that the sides are no longer in conflict with each other, through some sort of resolution between the two faces of the force. And that is my explanation as to why they had clips from the other movies. I mean it is also a little about milking money and that's why they chose to bring Anakin's story to light more through the trailer, but Disney did it with story intentions in mind with the story also making them do it. But its mainly what I said. The trilogy could have been done better, like filling in some holes that are explained in the greater canon universe and explaining more things in general, because that would have helped with all of this. But when it comes down to it, you need to spend hours late at night scrolling through different Star Wars analyses and theories on your phone not sleeping and also watch the movies a ton and constantly as well as the different tv shows and watch videos explaining the canon comics and books, because what else are you going to do at night other than avoid sleep by scrolling through youtube until two in the morning. Definitely the prequels and sequels biggest flaws are their utter lack of explanation of the greater story arc taking place. And that is most likely most do to George Lucas, because he wants things very much his way, and gets stressed out like real bad when they don't go his way, so he probably very much made sure it was exactly to his specifications (the level of an extremely accomplished critical thinker, writer, and creative everything, leading to him to be eccentric in his writing and making things much to convoluded for people to just understand like he does because somewhere in his mind he expects us all to just understand what he is doing even though we need like hours and hours of work to try and piece his crap together). There that's that.
